<page xml:id="p-5-2-similar-matrices">
    <title>Similar Matrices</title>

    <definition xml:id="def-similar-matrices">
      <title>Similarity</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Two <m>n\times n</m> matrices <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are <em>similar</em> if there exists an invertible matrix <m>P</m> such that
        </p>
        <me>
          A=PBP^{-1}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-similar-same-charpoly">
      <title>Characteristic Polynomial of Similar Matrices</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are similar, then they have the same characteristic polynomial.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <p>
      Notes:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        Our textbook introduces similar matrices in Section 5.2; many exercises appear in Section 5.3.
      </li>
      <li>
        Two matrices need not be similar to have the same eigenvalues. For example,
        <me>
          \begin{bmatrix}
            0 \amp 1\\
            0 \amp 0
          \end{bmatrix}
          \quad\text{and}\quad
          \begin{bmatrix}
            0 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 0
          \end{bmatrix}
        </me>
        share eigenvalues but are not similar (nilpotent vs. zero).
      </li>
    </ul>
  </page>
